And there it is, by a hair right now but likely to grow further. Since this is the question I was most invested in forecasting recently, I'm doing a quick hindsight examination of my rationales. Broadly: pretty good, but also somewhat lucky. I think all five underlying conditions I posited here (https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1060600) seem to have been correct, as was the use of slower-but-longer-growth version of first wave NY as my main comparison point. Working from those assumptions, the growth curve was fairly predictable, and my updates (https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1064318) seem to have been pretty much on point. Where does the luck come in? If we'd been asked to forecast deaths instead of hospitalizations, I think I would have posited the same underlying conditions and then been very wrong in my forecasts (similarly to how I just can't seem to get a handle on how the data is moving in the AZ ICU question). I'm proud of the reads I made on this question, but I also think the data "played nice" here to an unusual extent, and there are many similar questions I would have been much less accurate on.

Hospitalizations in Texas have been increasing recently. There are 2,242 hospitalizations statewide as of today (6/13) [1]. The bulk of cases are in the 20-59 age demographic, but the bulk of fatalities are in the 60+ demographic [2]. The number of daily fatalities is not increasing, so it's possible the increase in hospitalizations involves younger patients who can recover and leave the hospital more quickly than older patients. With Summer coming on, hospitalizations may be near peak (assuming COVID-19 has seasonal characteristics).

To give some data points to start with: - NY state had a high point of 18,825 hospitalizations in mid-April [1], with about 10k positive cases around that time - NJ had a high of 8,045 in mid-April [2], with about 3.5k positive cases per day around that time

My assumption is that on average there will be an additional net hospitalization trend of about 100 persons per week, i.e. 200 persons being released from hospital, while at the same time 300 will be hospitalized. I assume this effect will continue for the next 9 weeks (9 August 2020) with a slim tendency down in the net hospitalizations (120 down to 70). Then, for most of the time in August the net effect will be zero or less: since everybody is in holiday, sitting at home watching netflix or lying on the beaches, new confirmed infections will fall and together with it, the number of hospitalizations will fall. Latter will fall below release rate from hospital, in combination with an ever increasing death rate in ICU hospitalizations. 9 weeks times 100 hospitalizations on average leaves roughly 2,650 as a result in the maximum.

There were ~20,000 total hospitalizations in NY at one point during the first wave of the pandemic. This was when there were ~10,000 new cases per day. At this point, there are ~2,000 new cases per day in Texas. This shows that (AT THIS POINT), thereâ€™s ~20% of the cases in Texas but only ~10% of the hospitalizations NY experienced. Assuming a change in hospitalizations of ~10%, (the rate in NY as stated above), this implies an increase of ~200 beds each day while at this level. The existing hospitalizations are 2,166 as of June 12 and have increased by ~22% from 1,773 on June 2nd. Assuming the rate of increase in cases is constant instead of exponential for simplicity purposes, 200 new hospitalizations (technically the change in hospitalizations) would be 22% higher every 10 days, or eventually reaching ~975 by the end of August. Assuming all else remains constant, the month of August alone would have significantly more than 10,000 total hospitalizations. That said, there are obviously a multitude of other factors, including the rate at which people are released, changes in policy restricting activities, personal adherence to policies or recommendations, etc. Due to the liberty Texas has and the resistance it would likely face reimplementing any lock downs, I believe Taxes will wait as long as possible to act which will therefore allow the coronavirus to spread substantially. So, I believe the number of total hospitalizations will be more than 10,000 at some point prior to August 31st.
